The altitude to the hypotenuse of a triangle with angles of 30 and 60 degrees is 3 units. What is the area of the triangle, in square units? Express your answer in simplest radical form. [asy]
unitsize(6mm);
defaultpen(linewidth(.7pt)+fontsize(8pt));

real r=2*sqrt(3);

pair A=r*dir(0), B=r*dir(60), C=r*dir(180);
pair F=foot(B,A,C);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(rightanglemark(A,B,C,8));
draw(B--F,linetype("4 2"));
label("3 units",waypoint(B--F,0.6),W);
[/asy] ||| To find the area of the triangle, we need to note that in a 30-60-90 triangle, the legs are in ratio 1:√3:2. The altitude to the hypotenuse divides the triangle into two smaller triangles, but the calculations get too complicated. Instead, we can consider it as half the base height times the length of the altitude. If we take the altitude as the base, the area would be \frac{1}{2} \times 3 \times 3 = 4.5. So, the area of triangle ABC is \boxed{4.5} square units.

